<P>
MICHIGAN SENATE VOTES BAN ON KEVORKIAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Michigan Senate, seeking to prevent Dr. Jack Kevorkian from counseling 
terminally ill people about suicide, approved a permanent ban against the 
practice Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
 A temporary ban expired last month when a state commission failed to reach a 
consensus.Since then, legislators have been working to come up with a permanent 
ban to prevent Kevorkian from participating in any additional suicides. 
</P>
<P>
 Kevorkian's attorney, Geoffrey Fieger, called the bill "laughable" and said 
the Legislature is ignoring the wishes of the people. 
</P>
<P>
 Kevorkian has helped 21 people commit suicide since 1990. He faces two murder 
charges stemming from assisted suicides in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
 The measure must also be approved by the Michigan House of Representatives. 
</P>
<P>
 The ban sets a penalty of four years in prison and a $2,000 fine. 
</P>
