<HEADLINE>
<P>
PILGRIM GROUP MUTUAL FUNDS TO BREAK UP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TOM PETRUNO, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After months of controversy that drained its assets, the Century City-based 
Pilgrim Group mutual fund company said Wednesday that it will disband. 
</P>
<P>
 The firm said its staff and six of its 10 funds, with assets of $1.15 billion, 
will be sold to Express America Holdings, an Arizona mortgage banker, for $28 
million. 
</P>
<P>
 Pilgrim CEO Palomba Weingarten will retain four other Pilgrim funds with $750 
million in assets -- Pilgrim Adjustable U.S. Government Securities Trust, 
Pilgrim Adjustable Rate Securities Trust, Pilgrim Short-Term Multi-Market 
Income Fund II and Pilgrim All-Americas Government Income Trust -- under a 
corporate name yet to be chosen. 
</P>
<P>
 Weingarten was censured last spring by the National Assn. of Securities 
Dealers for ads that the NASD judged to be misleading. 
</P>
<P>
 Though penalties were reduced in September, the controversy surrounding her 
and the Pilgrim funds has caused business to fall off and prompted some fund 
shareholders to sell. Many industry analysts had speculated recently that the 
company would be sold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
