<TEXT>
<P>
 MEXICAN STOCKS 
</P>
<P>
 * Mexican stocks closed almost flat. Investors are nervous about rebel threats 
in the southern state of Chiapas to call off a cease-fire if the governor-elect 
for the state takes office today. 
</P>
<P>
 * Also keeping a lid on on market was a slight weakening of the Mexican 
currency. The spot dollar closed in Mexico City at 3.4495 from 3.4465 Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 * Telefonos de Mexico SA, Mexico's largest telecommunications company, is 
currently negotiating a general rate increase of about 4%, but will cut the 
cost of international long-distance calls by between 5% and 15%, a newspaper 
said. Telmex will lose its monopoly on long-distance in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
 The Bolsa Index 
</P>
<P>
 Wednesday closes: 2,520.89 
</P>
<P>
 Sources: Dow Jones; Bloomberg Business News SPOTLIGHT: IRELAND 
</P>
<P>
 The 1993 European currency crisis forced a 10% currency devaluation to keep 
Irish goods competitive. Other recent economic initiatives include reform of 
domestic industrial policy and a development plan -- targeting investment in 
certain industries and job training to create 200,000 jobs over the next six 
years. 
</P>
